[codex]   71: First, the paper, as written, feels a bit dated in several spots (e.g., early intro, then pp.4-5, and Discussion) given all that has transpired with respect to pull back on DEI commitments and practices in the US. ItΓÇÖs not clear how many companies are still providing diversity scorecards or numerical feedback about demographic representation, but itΓÇÖs certainly a smaller number than when this research project began, and perhaps, more importantly, the broader tides have shifted. The one sentence on p.5 ΓÇô ΓÇ£and despiteΓÇªΓÇ¥ - is not sufficient and is perhaps misleading. The authors should find a way to acknowledge this through the narrative, and more accurately depict the current state so that the article does not feel timestamped and detached as if it was written in a pre-2024 period. While doing this, they should find a way to reinforce the reasons why their question and intervention remain important.
[codex]   72: RESPONSE: Thank you for this comment. We have updated the Introduction (pp. X) and the Discussion to try to avoid the issue that it could read as ΓÇ£timestampedΓÇ¥ either in the current era in which there has been backlash against DEI (which may or may not endure) or in the post-2020, pre-2024 era of massively increasing support for DEI in the United States.
[codex]   73: The revised manuscript now more thoroughly discusses the fluctuating corporate posture toward DEI in the United States while noting that despite changing tides domestically, regulatory demand for transparency around demographic representation is expanding internationally. For example, AustraliaΓÇÖs Workplace Gender Equality Amendment (Closing the Gender Pay Gap) Act 2023 mandates public reporting of firm-level gender representation and pay-gap data (Ressia, 2024); the EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970 requires member-state transposition by June 2026 (Mignano, 2024); and the EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381 establishes a 40% representation objective for the underrepresented gender on listed-company boards. Second, within the U.S., public and stakeholder sentiment has shifted more slowly than corporate and legal rhetoric. For instance a 2025 Bentley/Gallup survey reports that 69% of U.S. adults believe businesses should promote DEI (Bentley/Gallup, 2025), and anti-DEI shareholder proposals have failed at numerous prominent organizations, including Costco, Apple, LeviΓÇÖs, John Deere, Goldman Sachs, and others (CBS, 2025; Marketplace, 2025). Third, many U.S. firms appear to have simply rebranded or reframed diversity-related work rather than dismantling it entirely since 2024. For example, Constellation Brands now uses ΓÇ£Inclusive Culture Team,ΓÇ¥ KohlΓÇÖs has shifted to ΓÇ£Chief Inclusion and Belonging Officer,ΓÇ¥ and Nationwide and UPS have migrated toward ΓÇ£belonging,ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£respect,ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£fairness,ΓÇ¥ or ΓÇ£inclusive experiencesΓÇ¥ framings (CNBC, 2025; HRGrapevine, 2025; Marketplace, 2026). Consistent with this pattern, Paradigm reports a 22% decrease in Fortune 100 references to ΓÇ£DEI/diversityΓÇ¥ between 2023 and 2024 alongside a 59% increase in references to ΓÇ£belongingΓÇ¥ (Paradigm, 2025).This comment helped us sharpen our discussion of why the paperΓÇÖs central question remains timeless. The paperΓÇÖs contribution is not simply to demonstrate that descriptive feedback may serve as a useful managerial tool for organizations seeking to enhance their diversity. Instead, it is to show that descriptive feedback about past selection decisions can change subsequent decisions when the patterns highlighted raise concerns about appearing prejudiced or failing to live up to your own egalitarian standards. To the extent that corporate messaging and formal diversity commitments are one source of peopleΓÇÖs motivation to respond without prejudice, their retreat may weaken the effects weΓÇÖve documented. However, such organizational commitments are only one small reason why people prefer not to behave in ways that could be seen as prejudiced. Anti-discrimination law, international transparency requirements, employee and stakeholder expectations, and individualsΓÇÖ own egalitarian commitments continue to make race and gender consequential dimensions of evaluation, even when organizations no longer foreground DEI policies. We now explain that descriptive feedback should be most influential when past selection patterns raise active concerns about prejudice, and less influential in contexts where those concerns are absent, muted, or explicitly rejected. Practically, this also reinforces the relevance of studying descriptive feedback: in settings where organizations are reluctant to issue explicit diversity goals, it remains important to understand whether making past selection patterns visible can still shape who is subsequently selected, hired, promoted, platformed, or featured.
