[codex] 41: RESPONSE: Thank you for this suggestion. We ran the post-test you proposed and incorporated the result into the Methods section of Study 1 (p. X). Specifically, in new pre-registered study ([link to AsPredicted]), we recruited 300 Prolific participants to rate the importance of different attributes of experts selected to appear on NPR.  Specifically, our Study 1 offers participants feedback about the gender, age, location and employment status of a panel of 6? NPR experts who they selected for [what was the selection about again? Remind reader!].  Our new study randomly assigned each participant to rate the importance of one of these four attributes of NPR experts (specifically: how many were women, how many worked at a university, how many were under 50 years old, or how many were based on the West Coast of the United States) on a scale from 1 = XX to 7 = XX. . Two of the three non-gender attributes were rated as significantly more important than gender (ΓÇ£were womenΓÇ¥; Mean Importance = 3.64, SD = 1.76, n = 76): ΓÇ£worked at a universityΓÇ¥ (Mean Importance = 4.67, SD = 1.60; t(148.8) = ΓêÆ3.76, p < .001, d = ΓêÆ0.61) and ΓÇ£were under 50 years oldΓÇ¥ (Mean Importance = 4.44, SD = 1.73; t(149.0) = ΓêÆ2.81, p = .006, d = ΓêÆ0.46). The third, ΓÇ£based on the West Coast of the United States,ΓÇ¥ did not differ significantly from gender in importance (Mean Importance = 3.37, SD = 1.75; t(149.0) = 0.95, p = .343, d = +0.16). These results suggest that differences in the perceived importance of the type of feedback participants received about their selections in Study 1 cannot account for why only feedback about gender moved subsequent selections.
[codex] 44: We expect that a reputational or image concern is activated only after participants receive descriptive feedback suggesting that women and minorities have been vastly underrepresented in their past selections compared to the U.S. population. If underrepresentation of any group is responsible for our effects, then if the descriptive feedback we provided on some other selection attribute (say, the age of prior selectees) suggested a massive underrepresentation (say, of people over 50), this might drive a similar reaction. We conducted an additional analysis to try to address this possibility. Assuming that selecting 0 people with a given attribute would always signal underrepresentation, we test the hypothesis that feedback shifts in who is subsequently selected to make up for underrepresentation not just when it comes to race and gender but on any dimension. To examine this hypothesis, we pooled data from Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B (clustering standard errors by participant). We exclude Study 4A from this analysis because no participants in that study made initial selections containing zero of any of the comparison attributes, meaning there is no comparable ΓÇ£zero-baselineΓÇ¥ cell to contrast against the race/gender effect. We look only at observations involving participants who made an initial set of selections that included zero people, books, or movies with a given attribute (e.g., a set of films in Study X that included 0 YΓÇÖs or a set of books in Study Z that included 0 YΓÇÖs). We find that among participants who selected zero women or racial minorities initially, across all studies, race and gender feedback significantly increases the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority as their final selection, respectively, by 21.28 percentage points (p < .001, N = 1,222). Among participants who initially selected zero movies, books or XX with any of the other attributes under study (e.g., X, Y or Z), feedback informing them that 0% of their selectees had those other attributes did not significantly increase their probability of subsequently selecting an additional movie book, or XX with the relevant attribute (estimated effect =+6.83 percentage point; p = .21, N = 429). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients confirms that the pooled effect of feedback on subsequent choices is significantly larger when feedback is about the race or gender of initial selections than when it is about other features of initial selections (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.70, +26.21]). We have added several sentences to the Discussion section of Study 4 (p. X) summarizing these analyses and pointing the interested reader to a new appendix section describing the results in more detail.
