[codex] revision-analysis/_r1_review\r1_response_draft_v2.md:13:> That said, we can examine directly what happens when feedback flags zero representation of the focal attribute. Among participants whose initial selection contained zero of an attribute, the inference that the attribute is "missing" from the initial set could itself produce some directional motivation to select one of those candidates next, independent of any injunctive norm; if our race/gender feedback effects were driven by this inference rather than by an underlying norm, we would expect comparable feedback effects on the comparison attributes among the subset of participants who picked zero of them initially. We do not observe that. Pooling participants across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B in a study-by-attribute fixed-effects regression with participant-clustered standard errors, restricted to the participant-attribute observations in which the initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute, race/gender feedback increases the probability of selecting a candidate with the focal attribute by +21.28 percentage points (*p* < .0001, *N* = 1,222 across all five studies), while comparison-attribute feedback increases that probability by only +6.83 percentage points, which is not statistically distinguishable from zero (*p* = .21, *N* = 429 across six attribute-by-study cells; the remaining nine cells are omitted because the comparison attribute is common in its candidate pool and almost no participant picked zero of it initially). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients yields +14.46 percentage points (*p* = .016, 95% CI [+2.70, +26.21]).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r1_review\r1_response_draft_v2.md:30:| **Pooled** (study-by-attribute FE; participant-clustered SE) | **+21.28\*\*\*** (*N* = 1,222) [+16.15, +26.42] | +6.83 (*N* = 429) [ΓêÆ3.81, +17.46] |
[codex] revision-analysis/_r1_review\r1_response_draft_v2.md:39:> Γü┐ Consistent with the account that descriptive feedback operates by surfacing an implicit injunctive norm, a complementary analysis pooled across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B shows that race/gender feedback continues to shift the final selection even among participants whose initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute (pooled +21.28 percentage points, *p* < .0001, *N* = 1,222), whereas comparison-attribute feedback does not (pooled +6.83 percentage points, *p* = .21, *N* = 429 across the six attribute-by-study cells in which a zero-initial subgroup is estimable; the remaining nine cells are omitted because the attribute is common in its candidate pool and almost no participant picked zero of it initially). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients yields +14.46 percentage points (*p* = .016, 95% CI [+2.70, +26.21]). This pattern is consistent with our broader claim that descriptive feedback shifts behavior on a given dimension only when participants carry an implicit injunctive norm about that dimension that the feedback can surface, which we observe for race and gender but not for the comparison attributes we test. Per-cell estimates are reported in Table R1 of the response letter.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:21:When designing our experiments, we aimed to select comparison attributes that would be highly relevant and important to each specific decision task. For example, in Study 3B (previously Study 1A), where participants selected biographical films for a Facebook advertising campaign, we included attributes central to film evaluation: budget (distinguishing blockbusters from independent films), year of release (indicating contemporary relevance), and the protagonistΓÇÖs profession (capturing the filmΓÇÖs core material). 
[codex] revision-analysis/_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:128:To clarify our theoretical contribution: our focus is on understanding when and why descriptive feedback about the race or gender composition of past selectees motivates people to subsequently pick more racial minorities or women, respectively. The primary purpose of our comparison feedback conditions was to rule out a simple demand effect explanation; that is, we include these other feedback items to demonstrate that providing any type of descriptive feedback does not automatically change behavior simply because participants respond to experimenters highlighting any attribute. Our comparison conditions show that feedback about other relevant attributes of past selections (e.g., in the case of films: budget, year of release, protagonistΓÇÖs profession) produces significantly smaller effects than feedback about race and gender, even when those other attributes show comparable levels of underrepresentation (as in Study 1).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:133:Maybe that itself is a bad category, but I wonder if you pre-tested a list of things that ΓÇ£people probably care aboutΓÇ¥ or ΓÇ£think is relevantΓÇ¥ in each domain, you could then find things that fit your prejudice/reputational criterion and those that don't and test your mechanisms more (e.g., What if with the books you included that people selections were primarily fiction or non-fiction? What if you highlighted that they picked mainly documentaries? What if they were putting together a team and you highlighted they had too much sales and not enough marketing?). To be clear, what IΓÇÖm proposing here is not circular. For your explanation, it should be the case that you can find stim that are highly relevant to a decision-maker, but have nothing to do with reputational concerns. Your thought is that those stim should not show your effect, but IΓÇÖm not so sure. An experiment would be best for this, but at the very least IΓÇÖd like the authors to discuss this more.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:135:When designing our experiments, we aimed to select comparison attributes that would be highly relevant and important to each specific decision task. For example, in Study 3A and 3B (previously Study 1A and 1B), where participants selected biographical films for a Facebook advertising campaign, we included attributes central to film evaluation: budget (distinguishing blockbusters from independent films), year of release (indicating contemporary relevance), and the protagonistΓÇÖs profession (capturing the filmΓÇÖs core material). But we take your point that our intuitions about the importance of attributes could have been wrong.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:162:This leaves open some questions in my mind. A general question is whether the dynamics animated by this set of studies would or would not translate to the constraints, motives, and concerns of employees embedded in an actual organization. A more specific elaboration of this question is: does the mindset of a survey panel participant or passerby at a university asked about general pop culture topics (e.g., preferences regarding books and movies) differ from an employee embedded in an organization, monitored by supervisors, subject to evaluation, etc.? I can imagine that for the former group, concerns about acting in concert with social appropriateness norms regarding gender and race are salient because they don't have any other immediate evaluative concerns or consequences to consider in the context of the studies. This creates a situation in which these concerns are perhaps more important than non-race/gender ones. For an employee, I wonder if the relative power of the race/gender feedback to change future decisions would be more contingent on what the organization and/or supervisors value, incentivize, punish, etc. If, for example, an employee gets feedback about patterns with respect to university affiliation or years of experience among candidates selectedΓÇöand these are factors the organization has made clear are important and consequential for employeesΓÇöthen would they be just as effective as race/gender feedback, or even more so? Take another possibility: what about a male dominated company that tolerates a culture of machismo or chauvinism ΓÇô would gender composition feedback still have the same unique impact? I think these questions speak to important contextual features that may constrain or complicate the general ΓÇ£race/gender feedback is uniquely motivatingΓÇ¥ interpretation running through the paper. Certainly, in some situations, concerns about appearing sexist/prejudice matter a lot, and more so than other factors; in other circumstances these concerns may be on par with, or even less prominent, than other issues that the organization values.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:197:RESPONSE: Thank you for noting the need for greater precision about the type of feedback we study. We have made sure to clarify in our introduction (see p. 3) how descriptive feedback differs from other feedback interventions. More specifically, we discuss how descriptive feedback, defined as simply stating the prevalence of past selections with certain characteristics (e.g., ΓÇ£20% of your selections featured women protagonistsΓÇ¥), is different from feedback containing normative or prescriptive targets. For example, descriptive feedback does not provide base rates (e.g., ΓÇ£compared to 40% available in the candidate poolΓÇ¥), peer comparisons (e.g., ΓÇ£others selected 35% womenΓÇ¥), or prescriptive targets (e.g., ΓÇ£the goal is 50% womenΓÇ¥).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:212:Study 1 is an organizational vignette in which participants assume a professional role as NPR producers selecting experts to interview for stories about the future of work. They are told to imagine that they have already selected 10 experts over the past three months (instead of making their own selections as in our other studies). At this point, we share feedback about the attributes of the 10 experts weΓÇÖve asked them to imagine they selected.
