[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v3_codex.md:34:> We have addressed your two empirical requests. First, the new Study 1 importance post-test (N = 300) confirms that differences in perceived attribute importance cannot explain why only gender feedback moved subsequent selections: two of the three comparison attributes were rated significantly more important than gender, and the third did not differ. Second, to address the alternative that comparison attributes are already selected at appropriate levels initially, we restrict to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute and report a new pooled analysis across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B (response-letter Table R1). Because we cannot observe each participantΓÇÖs private view of the ΓÇ£appropriateΓÇ¥ level for a given attribute, zero is a useful but imperfect floor that lets us hold a common starting point across focal and comparison attributes. If feedback merely corrected under-selection relative to private benchmarks, it should move participants for both race/gender and comparison attributes in this subset. Instead, race and gender feedback increases subsequent selection of the focal attribute (+21.28 pp, p < .001, N = 1,222), whereas comparison-attribute feedback does not reliably do so (+6.83 pp, p = .21, N = 429); the Wald-test difference is +14.46 pp (p = .016). We treat this analysis as imperfect but directional evidence against the alternative that participants were simply selecting comparison attributes at appropriate levels to begin with.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v3_codex.md:89:- Numbers and citations: retained the requested values and lists: +21.28 pp, +6.83 pp, +14.46 pp, p = .016, N = 300, N = 1,222, N = 429, 69% Bentley/Gallup, the full contemporary reference list, and Costco, Apple, LeviΓÇÖs, John Deere, and Goldman Sachs. I did not identify a mismatch against the two supplied files after the edits above.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_second_pass.session.log:612:[codex] 46: Additional analysis: Although we don╬ô├ç├ût have data to perfectly speak to this, we conducted an additional analysis to try to address this concern. We can hold the starting point constant by restricting to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute. We cannot directly measure what each participant considers an ╬ô├ç┬úappropriate╬ô├ç┬Ñ level for a given attribute, but zero is a reasonable floor and is unlikely to reflect a deliberate level for most participants. In this analysis, we test the hypothesis that feedback motivates selection whenever the initial selections do not reflect appropriate levels. If that were the case, we should see feedback move participants for both race and gender and the comparison attributes in this subset. To test this hypothesis, we pooled participants across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B with participant-clustered standard errors, restricted to participant observations in which the initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute. We find that among participants who selected zero women or racial minorities initially, race and gender feedback increases the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority as their final selection by +21.28 percentage points (p < .001, N = 1,222 across all five studies). Among participants who selected zero individuals any of the other attributes, feedback about these other attributes increases the probability of selecting an additional individual with that attribute by only +6.83 percentage points, and is not statistically significant (p = .21, N = 429). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients yields +14.46 percentage points (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.70, +26.21]). See Table R1 for full results.  We have also added a footnote to the Discussion of Study 4 (p. X) that summarizes this evidence
