[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_session.log:1025:[codex] 33: We established across all seven experiments in this paper that in settings where women (or racial minorities) are underrepresented, providing descriptive feedback about the gender (or race) of past selectees alongside other feedback about past selectees╬ô├ç├û characteristics increases evaluators╬ô├ç├û subsequent likelihood of selecting women (or racial minorities). In Study 2, we established the external validity of our findings through a framed field experiment (on a university campus). To further establish that our findings are not merely driven by a demand effect, we also showed that the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender or race of past selectees is reliably and significantly larger than that of providing descriptive feedback about other attributes of past selectees (e.g., the fraction in a given profession, the fraction in a given birth cohort) on participants╬ô├ç├û likelihood of selecting candidates with those other attributes (e.g., a candidate in a given profession or a given birth cohort), even when those other attributes are rated as similarly important as candidates╬ô├ç├û demographics (Studies 1, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B). In Studies 4A and 4B, we showed that motivation to respond without prejudice mediated the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender (or race) of past selectees on the likelihood of subsequently selecting a woman (or racial minority) candidate. And finally, in Study 5, we showed that providing feedback about the percentage of past selectees who were women only subsequently increased the selection of women when women are underrepresented in the initial candidate pool; when women are overrepresented, the effect is significantly smaller in magnitude and reverses in direction (decreasing the selection of women), and is mediated by fairness concerns rather than concerns about prejudice.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v1.md:67:> We have addressed your two empirical requests. First, the new Study 1 importance postΓÇætest (N = 300; one comparison attribute rated per participant) confirms that differences in perceived attribute importance cannot account for why only gender feedback moved subsequent selections: two of the three comparison attributes were rated significantly more important than the gender attribute, and the third did not differ in rated importance. Second, to address the alternative that comparison attributes are simply being selected at appropriate levels in participants' initial selections, we report a new pooled analysis (responseΓÇæletter Table R1) restricted to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute, pooling across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B with participantΓÇæclustered standard errors. Race and gender feedback raises the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority by +21.28 percentage points (p < .001, N = 1,222) in this restricted subset, while comparisonΓÇæattribute feedback raises it by only +6.83 percentage points (p = .21, N = 429); the WaldΓÇætest difference is +14.46 pp (p = .016).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v1.md:107:   - **Numbers and citations.** SpotΓÇæcheck author names, years, and specific numbers (e.g., +21.28 pp, +6.83 pp, +14.46 pp, p = .016, N = 300, 69% Bentley/Gallup) against the body of the letter and (where possible) the manuscript.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_review.log:55:> We have addressed your two empirical requests. First, the new Study 1 importance postΓÇætest (N = 300) confirms that differences in perceived attribute importance cannot explain why only gender feedback moved subsequent selections: two of the three comparison attributes were rated significantly more important than gender, and the third did not differ. Second, to address the alternative that comparison attributes are already selected at appropriate levels initially, we restrict to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute and report a new pooled analysis across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B (responseΓÇæletter Table R1). Zero is a defensible benchmark precisely because we cannot observe each participant's private notion of "appropriate": anyone whose initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute is necessarily below any plausible such benchmark. If feedback merely corrected underΓÇæselection relative to a private benchmark, it should move participants for both race/gender and comparison attributes in this subset. Instead, only race and gender feedback does (+21.28 pp, p < .001, N = 1,222), while comparisonΓÇæattribute feedback does not (+6.83 pp, p = .21, N = 429); the WaldΓÇætest difference is +14.46 pp (p = .016).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_review.log:131:That said, we can hold the starting point constant by restricting to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute. We cannot directly measure what each participant considers an ΓÇ£appropriateΓÇ¥ level for a given attribute, but zero is a reasonable floor and is unlikely to reflect a deliberate level for most participants. In this analysis, we test the hypothesis that feedback motivates selection whenever the initial selections do not reflect appropriate levels. If that were the case, we should see feedback move participants for both race and gender and the comparison attributes in this subset. To test this hypothesis, we pooled participants across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B with participant-clustered standard errors, restricted to participant observations in which the initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute. We find that race and gender feedback increases the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority by +21.28 percentage points (p < .001, N = 1,222 across all five studies). Whereas, feedback about other attributes increases that probability by only +6.83 percentage points, and is not statistically significant (p = .21, N = 429). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients yields +14.46 percentage points (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.70, +26.21]).
