[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:275:[codex] Additional analysis: Although we don╬ô├ç├ût have data to perfectly speak to this, we conducted an additional analysis to try to address this concern. We can hold the starting point constant by restricting to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute. We cannot directly measure what each participant considers an ╬ô├ç┬úappropriate╬ô├ç┬Ñ level for a given attribute, but zero is a reasonable floor and is unlikely to reflect a deliberate level for most participants. In this analysis, we test the hypothesis that feedback motivates selection whenever the initial selections do not reflect appropriate levels. If that were the case, we should see feedback move participants for both race and gender and the comparison attributes in this subset. To test this hypothesis, we pooled participants across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B with participant-clustered standard errors, restricted to participant observations in which the initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute. We find that among participants who selected zero women or racial minorities initially, race and gender feedback increases the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority as their final selection by +21.28 percentage points (p < .001, N = 1,222 across all five studies). Among participants who selected zero individuals any of the other attributes, feedback about these other attributes increases the probability of selecting an additional individual with that attribute by only +6.83 percentage points, and is not statistically significant (p = .21, N = 429). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients yields +14.46 percentage points (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.70, +26.21]). See Table R1 for full results.  We have also added a footnote to the Discussion of Study 4 (p. X) that summarizes this evidence
