[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:1241:[codex] Note: Across all experiments, participants received descriptive feedback about their initial selection decisions. Forest plots illustrate the percentage point differences in participants╬ô├ç├û subsequent selection decisions induced by descriptive feedback. (A) This graph shows consistent and positive effects of providing descriptive feedback about the gender (Studies 1, 2, 3B, and 4B) and race (Studies 3A and 4A) of past selectees on the subsequent selections of women (Studies 1, 2, 3B, and 4B) and racial minorities (Studies 3A and 4A). (B) This graph shows smaller and directionally inconsistent effects of providing descriptive feedback about other relevant attributes of past selectees (e.g., Study 3B: whether the film╬ô├ç├ûs protagonist was a political leader, whether the budget of the film was above $40M, whether the film was released after 2010) on subsequent selection decisions. The gray circles show average effects pools, while the gray diamonds show the disaggregated effects of feedback on specific, targeted attributes. Positive values indicate a positive effect of random assignment to receive a certain type of descriptive feedback on the likelihood of subsequently selecting a candidate with that targeted attribute, while negative values indicate a negative response. The error bars represent 95% confidence intervals.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:1277:[codex]   16: People╬ô├ç├ûs drive to respond without prejudice can be a powerful motivator of behavior change, influencing such outcomes as their willingness to refer racial minorities for professional development opportunities (Kirgios et al., 2022) and time invested in prejudice-reducing training (Plant & Devine, 2009). More broadly, past research has demonstrated that people are motivated to conform to the implicit injunctive norms╬ô├ç├╢the norms about how a person should behave╬ô├ç├╢that they perceive to be prevalent in their cultures and organizations (Cialdini, Reno & Kallgren, 1990). While descriptive norms (information about what others do) can influence behavior by providing a social benchmark (Bicchieri & Xiao, 2009), injunctive norms influence behavior via the suggestion that there could be social sanctions for deviance or social rewards for compliance. In one demonstration of the power of injunctive norms╬ô├ç├û influence on behavior, a year-long field experiment in Rwanda tested the effects of exposure to a radio soap opera portraying characters who challenged prejudicial norms. This soap opera communicated an explicit injunctive norm that prejudicial behavior was unacceptable, and it changed listeners╬ô├ç├û behavior to be less prejudicial (Paluck, 2009).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:1294:[codex]   33: We established across all seven experiments in this paper that in settings where women (or racial minorities) are underrepresented, providing descriptive feedback about the gender (or race) of past selectees alongside other feedback about past selectees╬ô├ç├û characteristics increases evaluators╬ô├ç├û subsequent likelihood of selecting women (or racial minorities). In Study 2, we established the external validity of our findings through a framed field experiment (on a university campus). To further establish that our findings are not merely driven by a demand effect, we also showed that the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender or race of past selectees is reliably and significantly larger than that of providing descriptive feedback about other attributes of past selectees (e.g., the fraction in a given profession, the fraction in a given birth cohort) on participants╬ô├ç├û likelihood of selecting candidates with those other attributes (e.g., a candidate in a given profession or a given birth cohort), even when those other attributes are rated as similarly important as candidates╬ô├ç├û demographics (Studies 1, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B). In Studies 4A and 4B, we showed that motivation to respond without prejudice mediated the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender (or race) of past selectees on the likelihood of subsequently selecting a woman (or racial minority) candidate. And finally, in Study 5, we showed that providing feedback about the percentage of past selectees who were women only subsequently increased the selection of women when women are underrepresented in the initial candidate pool; when women are overrepresented, the effect is significantly smaller in magnitude and reverses in direction (decreasing the selection of women), and is mediated by fairness concerns rather than concerns about prejudice.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:1321:[codex]   60: Procedure. Student recruiters in school-branded clothing (truthfully) told passersby they were conducting a quick vote on which biographies should be displayed at the business school to encourage non-fiction reading; seven books with obscured covers on a table served as a visual prop (see Figure S1 in the Appendix). Participants who agreed were handed an iPad showing 25 well-known biographies, each with a cover thumbnail and a brief description (protagonist╬ô├ç├ûs name, role, publication year, page count); five (20%) featured women protagonists.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:1322:[codex]   61: Participants were instructed to vote for an initial portfolio of six biographies they would recommend for the on-campus display. After making their initial selections, participants were randomly assigned to either (1) the no gender feedback condition or (2) the gender feedback condition. In the no gender feedback condition, participants were presented with three pieces of descriptive feedback about their initial six book selections, specifically the percentage of biographies they had selected that (1) were over 500 pages, (2) were written in the past 25 years, and (3) featured an entertainer. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of biographies they had selected featuring a woman protagonist alongside two additional pieces of descriptive feedback that were randomly drawn from the list of three descriptive facts provided in the no gender feedback condition. After receiving descriptive feedback about the composition of their initial selected portfolio of six biographies, participants were asked to vote for a seventh and final biography from the original set╬ô├ç├┤where their prior selections were highlighted╬ô├ç├┤to include in the display.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:1327:[codex]   66: Initial selections featured women protagonists 25.2% of the time, with a slight imbalance across conditions (23.0% control vs. 27.3% treatment, p = .050). Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regression with robust standard errors to predict whether the seventh and final biography participants selected featured a woman. Participants were significantly more likely to choose a biography featuring a woman as their seventh and final selection in the gender feedback condition (35.10% did so) than in the no gender feedback condition (21.85% chose a woman; B = 0.132, 95% CI = [0.031, 0.234],Γö¼├ít(302) = 2.56,Γö¼├ípΓö¼├í= .011, see Figure 3; Table 3, Model 1).
