[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:1371:[codex]  110: Initial selections featured racial minority authors 21.8% of the time, with balance across conditions (pΓö¼├í= .114; see Appendix Table S7). Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regression with robust standard errors predicting whether the seventh and final author a participant selected was a racial minority, with assignment to the race feedback condition as the primary predictor. We again replicated the findings from our previous studies (see Table S7 for complete results): Participants were significantly more likely to choose a racial minority author in the race feedback condition (41.60% chose a racial minority author) than in the no race feedback condition (28.20% chose a racial minority author;Γö¼├íBΓö¼├í= 0.134, 95% CI = [0.075, 0.193],Γö¼├ít(998) = 4.48,Γö¼├ípΓö¼├í< .001; see Table S7, Model 1). In addition, as predicted, we again found that the effect of providing feedback about the race of initial selectees is significantly larger than the effects of providing descriptive feedback about other attributes of initial selectees (poets:Γö¼├íF(1, 3984) = 6.19,Γö¼├ípΓö¼├í= .013; wrote > 10 books:Γö¼├íF(1, 3984) = 5.50,Γö¼├ípΓö¼├í= .019; born in 1800s:Γö¼├íF(1, 3984) = 5.26,Γö¼├ípΓö¼├í= .022; see Table S7, Models 5-8).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:1379:[codex]  118: Procedure. As in Study 4A, a list of 25 (real) authors was presented to each participant to consider for inclusion in a reading list for their local library. Each author was displayed with a photograph, the author╬ô├ç├ûs name (e.g., Kurt Vonnegut), most notable work (e.g., Slaughterhouse-Five), an estimate of their most notable work╬ô├ç├ûs all-time sales and time in print (e.g., 800K copies sold, in print 56 years), their number of works authored (e.g., 14 books, 3 essays), and their genre(s) (e.g., Science Fiction, Satire). Six of the authors on this list (24%) were women.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:1425:[codex]  164: The results of this simulation exercise are summarized in Appendix Table S12 (and the complete regressions used to estimate the effect of each simulated quota condition are presented in detail in Appendix Table S14). For women in Study 2 (see Appendix Table S12, Row 1), compared to the control condition, the descriptive feedback intervention increased the likelihood that participants selected biographies featuring female protagonists by 13.2 percentage points (B = 0.132, 95% CI = [0.031, 0.234], p = .011), and the simulated quota also significantly increased selections, by 18.5% (B = 0.185, 95% CI = [0.082, 0.289], p < .001), meaning feedback produced 71.4% of the benefit of a quota. For racial minorities in Study 3A (see Appendix Table S12, Row 2), compared to the control condition, the descriptive feedback intervention increased the likelihood that participants selected films featuring racial minority protagonists by 9.4 percentage points (B = 0.094, 95% CI = [0.042, 0.145], p < .001), and the simulated quota also significantly increased selections, by 17.1% (B = 0.171, 95% CI = [0.118, 0.225], p < .001), meaning feedback produced 54.7% of the benefit of a quota. For women in Study 3B (see Appendix Table S12, Row 3), compared to control condition, the descriptive feedback intervention significantly increased the likelihood of selecting films featuring female protagonists by 20.6 percentage points (B = 0.206, 95% CI = [0.150, 0.261], p < .001), while the simulated quota also significantly increased selections by 25.7% (B = 0.257, 95% CI = [0.201, 0.313], p < .001). This means offering descriptive feedback on the gender of past films╬ô├ç├û protagonists yielded 80.0% of the benefit of a gender quota. In Study 4A (see Appendix Table S12, Row 4), which examined racial diversity in author selections, compared to the control condition the descriptive feedback intervention significantly increased the likelihood of selecting authors from racial minority backgrounds by 13.4 percentage points (B = 0.134, 95% CI = [0.075, 0.193], p < .001), while the simulated quota also significantly increased selections by 29.6% (B = 0.296, 95% CI = [0.237, 0.355], p < .001), relative to the control condition, meaning that feedback achieved 45.3% of the effect of a quota. Finally, in Study 4B (see Appendix Table S12, Row 5), which examined gender diversity in author selections, compared to the control condition the descriptive feedback intervention significantly increased the likelihood of selecting female authors by 11.9 percentage points (B = 0.119, 95% CI = [0.060, 0.178], p < .001), while the simulated quota also significantly increased selections by 15.6% (B = 0.156, 95% CI = [0.096, 0.215], p < .001), meaning feedback produced 76.7% of the benefit of a quota.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:1436:[codex]  175: While our large sample sizes, diverse stimuli, and pre-registered experiments have many strengths, our research also has several important limitations. First, most of our studies rely on a fairly consistent paradigm. However, we systematically varied several design features across studies, including organizational context (e.g., whether participants were selecting NPR guests, books to be displayed at a library or on campus, or leaders to speak at a large conference), the base rates of underrepresentation in candidate pools, and outcomes measured (the selection of a single woman/racial minority vs. the proportion of women selected in a set). In most organizational settings, selection decisions and feedback will be more spread out over time and candidate pools will be less constrained than in our studies. For example, one candidate might be hired per quarter, and feedback might be provided at the end of the calendar year. Future research confirming that the effect we╬ô├ç├ûve documented here still arises when people face unconstrained candidate pools and extended decision and feedback timelines would be valuable. While it is possible that an extended decision timeline would decrease the size of feedback effects because feedback can become less salient over time (Tiefenbeck et al., 2018), the effect could also be magnified. Given the strength of the reputational and self-image concerns involved in the types of decisions we study, having more time to deliberate may provide a greater opportunity for evaluators to actively regulate their decisions and implement even more substantial corrections (Fazio, 1990; Plant & Devine, 2009). Additionally, while Study 5 demonstrates that feedback produces different effects depending on whether women are underrepresented or overrepresented, future research could explore the precise threshold at which feedback shifts from triggering motivation to respond without prejudice to triggering fairness concerns, though this threshold is likely context dependent.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:1456:[codex] 33:We established across all seven experiments in this paper that in settings where women (or racial minorities) are underrepresented, providing descriptive feedback about the gender (or race) of past selectees alongside other feedback about past selectees╬ô├ç├û characteristics increases evaluators╬ô├ç├û subsequent likelihood of selecting women (or racial minorities). In Study 2, we established the external validity of our findings through a framed field experiment (on a university campus). To further establish that our findings are not merely driven by a demand effect, we also showed that the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender or race of past selectees is reliably and significantly larger than that of providing descriptive feedback about other attributes of past selectees (e.g., the fraction in a given profession, the fraction in a given birth cohort) on participants╬ô├ç├û likelihood of selecting candidates with those other attributes (e.g., a candidate in a given profession or a given birth cohort), even when those other attributes are rated as similarly important as candidates╬ô├ç├û demographics (Studies 1, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B). In Studies 4A and 4B, we showed that motivation to respond without prejudice mediated the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender (or race) of past selectees on the likelihood of subsequently selecting a woman (or racial minority) candidate. And finally, in Study 5, we showed that providing feedback about the percentage of past selectees who were women only subsequently increased the selection of women when women are underrepresented in the initial candidate pool; when women are overrepresented, the effect is significantly smaller in magnitude and reverses in direction (decreasing the selection of women), and is mediated by fairness concerns rather than concerns about prejudice.
