[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\gdoc_comments.json:56:      "value": "Second, to address the alternative that comparison attributes are already selected at appropriate levels initially, we restrict to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute and report a new pooled analysis across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B (see response letter Table R1). Because we cannot observe each participantΓÇÖs private view of the ΓÇ£appropriateΓÇ¥ level for a given attribute, zero is a useful but imperfect floor that lets us hold a common starting point across focal and comparison attributes. If feedback merely corrected underΓÇæselection relative to private benchmarks, it should move participants for both race, gender and comparison attributes in this subset. Instead, race and gender feedback increases subsequent selection of the focal attribute (+21.28 pp, p &lt; .001, N = 1,222), whereas comparisonΓÇæattribute feedback does not reliably do so (+6.83 pp, p = .21, N = 429); the WaldΓÇætest difference is +14.46 pp (p = .016). We treat this analyΓÇª"
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:16:PeopleΓÇÖs drive to respond without prejudice can be a powerful motivator of behavior change, influencing such outcomes as their willingness to refer racial minorities for professional development opportunities (Kirgios et al., 2022) and time invested in prejudice-reducing training (Plant & Devine, 2009). More broadly, past research has demonstrated that people are motivated to conform to the implicit injunctive normsΓÇöthe norms about how a person should behaveΓÇöthat they perceive to be prevalent in their cultures and organizations (Cialdini, Reno & Kallgren, 1990). While descriptive norms (information about what others do) can influence behavior by providing a social benchmark (Bicchieri & Xiao, 2009), injunctive norms influence behavior via the suggestion that there could be social sanctions for deviance or social rewards for compliance. In one demonstration of the power of injunctive normsΓÇÖ influence on behavior, a year-long field experiment in Rwanda tested the effects of exposure to a radio soap opera portraying characters who challenged prejudicial norms. This soap opera communicated an explicit injunctive norm that prejudicial behavior was unacceptable, and it changed listenersΓÇÖ behavior to be less prejudicial (Paluck, 2009).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:33:We established across all seven experiments in this paper that in settings where women (or racial minorities) are underrepresented, providing descriptive feedback about the gender (or race) of past selectees alongside other feedback about past selecteesΓÇÖ characteristics increases evaluatorsΓÇÖ subsequent likelihood of selecting women (or racial minorities). In Study 2, we established the external validity of our findings through a framed field experiment (on a university campus). To further establish that our findings are not merely driven by a demand effect, we also showed that the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender or race of past selectees is reliably and significantly larger than that of providing descriptive feedback about other attributes of past selectees (e.g., the fraction in a given profession, the fraction in a given birth cohort) on participantsΓÇÖ likelihood of selecting candidates with those other attributes (e.g., a candidate in a given profession or a given birth cohort), even when those other attributes are rated as similarly important as candidatesΓÇÖ demographics (Studies 1, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B). In Studies 4A and 4B, we showed that motivation to respond without prejudice mediated the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender (or race) of past selectees on the likelihood of subsequently selecting a woman (or racial minority) candidate. And finally, in Study 5, we showed that providing feedback about the percentage of past selectees who were women only subsequently increased the selection of women when women are underrepresented in the initial candidate pool; when women are overrepresented, the effect is significantly smaller in magnitude and reverses in direction (decreasing the selection of women), and is mediated by fairness concerns rather than concerns about prejudice.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:60:Procedure. Student recruiters in school-branded clothing (truthfully) told passersby they were conducting a quick vote on which biographies should be displayed at the business school to encourage non-fiction reading; seven books with obscured covers on a table served as a visual prop (see Figure S1 in the Appendix). Participants who agreed were handed an iPad showing 25 well-known biographies, each with a cover thumbnail and a brief description (protagonistΓÇÖs name, role, publication year, page count); five (20%) featured women protagonists.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:61:Participants were instructed to vote for an initial portfolio of six biographies they would recommend for the on-campus display. After making their initial selections, participants were randomly assigned to either (1) the no gender feedback condition or (2) the gender feedback condition. In the no gender feedback condition, participants were presented with three pieces of descriptive feedback about their initial six book selections, specifically the percentage of biographies they had selected that (1) were over 500 pages, (2) were written in the past 25 years, and (3) featured an entertainer. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of biographies they had selected featuring a woman protagonist alongside two additional pieces of descriptive feedback that were randomly drawn from the list of three descriptive facts provided in the no gender feedback condition. After receiving descriptive feedback about the composition of their initial selected portfolio of six biographies, participants were asked to vote for a seventh and final biography from the original setΓÇôwhere their prior selections were highlightedΓÇôto include in the display.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:66:Initial selections featured women protagonists 25.2% of the time, with a slight imbalance across conditions (23.0% control vs. 27.3% treatment, p = .050). Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regression with robust standard errors to predict whether the seventh and final biography participants selected featured a woman. Participants were significantly more likely to choose a biography featuring a woman as their seventh and final selection in the gender feedback condition (35.10% did so) than in the no gender feedback condition (21.85% chose a woman; B = 0.132, 95% CI = [0.031, 0.234],┬át(302) = 2.56,┬áp┬á= .011, see Figure 3; Table 3, Model 1).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:79:Procedure. Participants were truthfully informed about a real Facebook campaign to advertise popular and inspirational biographical films (ΓÇ£biopicsΓÇ¥) and asked to weigh in on which films to include. Participants saw25 candidate films each with a cover art thumbnail and a brief description listing the  protagonistΓÇÖs name (e.g., Judy Garland, Alan Turing), claim to fame (e.g., Actress, WWII codebreaker), the filmΓÇÖs year of release (e.g., 2019, 2014), and budget (e.g., $10m, $14m); 4 of the25 films (16%) featured a racial minority protagonist. 
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:81:Participants were then randomly assigned to either (1) the no race feedback or (2) the race feedback condition. In the no race feedback condition, participants received descriptive feedback on the percentage of films that (1) had a budget above $40M, (2) were released after 2010, and (3) were over 2 hours long. In the race feedback condition, participants always received descriptive feedback about the percentage of films they had selected that featured a racial minority protagonist alongside two randomly drawn pieces of feedback from the list of film attributes summarized in the no race feedback condition. After receiving descriptive feedback on their initial film selections, participants selected an eighth and final film for the Facebook campaign from the original set, where their prior selections were highlighted. See Materials Section: Study 3A in the Appendix for complete study materials.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:83:ParticipantsΓÇÖ initial selections featured racial minority protagonists 16.1% of the time, with balance across conditions (p┬á= .314, see Appendix Table S3). Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regression with robust standard errors to predict whether the eighth and final biopic selected featured a racial minority protagonist, using assignment to the race feedback condition as the primary predictor Participants were significantly more likely to choose a biopic featuring a racial minority protagonist in the race feedback condition (27.10% chose a biopic featuring a racial minority protagonist) than in the no race feedback condition (17.73% chose a biopic featuring a racial minority protagonist;┬áB┬á= 0.094, 95% CI = [0.042, 0.145],┬át(998) = 3.57,┬áp┬á< .001).The effect of assignment to the race feedback condition on the subsequent selection of a racial minority protagonist was significantly larger than the effects of assignment to receive descriptive feedback about any of the three comparison attributes (all pΓÇÖs Γëñ .009; see Table S3, Models 5-8 for the per-study system-of-equations results). 
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:88:Procedure. The procedure in this study was nearly identical to the procedure described in Study 3A, but we changed the selection set of biopics to include 19 films featuring male protagonists and 6 featuring female protagonists (so 24% of the protagonists were women). Participants also began by selecting an initial portfolio of six films for inclusion in the Facebook advertising campaign instead of seven. The brief description provided of each film did not state the length of the film; instead, it presented information about the film protagonistΓÇÖs profession (e.g., ΓÇ£A film about George W. Bush. Who was he? 43rd U.S. President.ΓÇ¥). 
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:89:Just as in the prior study, after making their set of six initial film selections, participants were randomly assigned to either (1) the no gender feedback condition or (2) the gender feedback condition. In the no gender feedback condition, participants were presented with feedback about the percentage of films they had selected that (1) had a budget above $40M, (2) were released after 2010, and (3) included a political leader as the protagonist. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of films they had selected featuring a woman protagonist, in addition to two more pieces of descriptive feedback randomly selected from the three in the no gender feedback condition. Otherwise, the study was identical to Study 3A. See Materials Section: Study 3B in the Appendix for complete study materials.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:91:On average, 17.5% of participantsΓÇÖ initially selected films featured female protagonists, with balance across conditions (p = 0.813; see Appendix Table/Section X). As shown in Figure S2B and in our primary, pre-registered OLS regression (Model 1 of Table S5), participants were significantly more likely to choose a biopic featuring a woman protagonist as their seventh and final film in the gender feedback condition (40.64% chose a biopic with a woman protagonist) than in the no gender feedback condition (20.08% chose a biopic with a woman protagonist; B = 0.206, 95% CI = [0.150, 0.261], t(998) = 7.24, p < .001, see Table S5 Model 1). These results were robust to several alternative specifications, including controlling for participant gender, race, and age, and analyzing our data with logistic regression (see Appendix Table S6 for robustness checks). In addition, as shown in Figure S2B and Table S5 (Models 5-8), and as predicted, the effect of assignment to the gender feedback condition on the likelihood of selecting a 7th film with a woman protagonist was larger than the effect of assignment to receive descriptive feedback about the percentage of initial films selected with a (1) budget above $40M (F(1, 1992) = 65.06, p < .001), (2) political leader protagonist (F(1, 1992) = 57.74, p < .001), or (3) release year after 2010 (F(1, 1992) = 12.44, p < .001) on subsequent selections of a 7th and final biopic with, respectively, a (1) budget above $40M, (2) political leader protagonist, or (3) release year after 2010 (in fact, all other types of feedback had insignificant effects on subsequent film selections).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:93:Across two incentivized experiments,  descriptive feedback about the race (Study 3A) or gender (Study 3B) of protagonists featured in previously selected films increased subsequent selections of films featuring racial minorities or women, respectively. One possible explanation for our findings is that the feedback itself signaled that we value racial or gender diversity: after initially choosing films based on personal preferences, participants may have inferred from race or gender feedback that these attributes mattered to the experimenter and attended to these attributes more in subsequent decisions as a result of a ΓÇ£demand effectΓÇ¥ (Orne, 1962; Zizzo, 2010). If this alternative explanation were driving our effects, however, we would also expect participants to respond to the ΓÇ£demand effectΓÇ¥ inherent in receiving feedback about other attributes of their selected films (e.g., feedback about a filmΓÇÖs budget or year of release), but we found no such patterns. 
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:104:Procedure. Participants imagined being  tasked with creating a reading list for their local library. They were presented with a 25 (real) authors, each shown with a small photograph and a brief description listing the authorΓÇÖs name (e.g., James Baldwin, Isabel Allende), most notable work (e.g., Go Tell It on the Mountain, The House of the Spirits), and a count of their total published works (e.g., ΓÇ£authored 6 books and several short stories and poemsΓÇ¥; ΓÇ£authored 6 booksΓÇ¥). Eight of the 25 authors (32%) were racial minorities.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:105:Participants selected an initial portfolio of six authors and were randomly assigned to one of two conditions: (1) the no race feedback condition or (2) the race feedback condition. In the no race feedback condition, participants received summary statistics about the percentage of selected authors who (1) were born in the 1800s, (2) wrote more than 10 books, and/or (3) wrote poetry. In the race feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of authors they had selected who were racial minorities, alongside one or two randomly drawn pieces of feedback from the list above.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:110:Initial selections featured racial minority authors 21.8% of the time, with balance across conditions (p┬á= .114; see Appendix Table S7). Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regression with robust standard errors predicting whether the seventh and final author a participant selected was a racial minority, with assignment to the race feedback condition as the primary predictor. We again replicated the findings from our previous studies (see Table S7 for complete results): Participants were significantly more likely to choose a racial minority author in the race feedback condition (41.60% chose a racial minority author) than in the no race feedback condition (28.20% chose a racial minority author;┬áB┬á= 0.134, 95% CI = [0.075, 0.193],┬át(998) = 4.48,┬áp┬á< .001; see Table S7, Model 1). In addition, as predicted, we again found that the effect of providing feedback about the race of initial selectees is significantly larger than the effects of providing descriptive feedback about other attributes of initial selectees (poets:┬áF(1, 3984) = 6.19,┬áp┬á= .013; wrote > 10 books:┬áF(1, 3984) = 5.50,┬áp┬á= .019; born in 1800s:┬áF(1, 3984) = 5.26,┬áp┬á= .022; see Table S7, Models 5-8).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:118:Procedure. As in Study 4A, a list of 25 (real) authors was presented to each participant to consider for inclusion in a reading list for their local library. Each author was displayed with a photograph, the authorΓÇÖs name (e.g., Kurt Vonnegut), most notable work (e.g., Slaughterhouse-Five), an estimate of their most notable workΓÇÖs all-time sales and time in print (e.g., 800K copies sold, in print 56 years), their number of works authored (e.g., 14 books, 3 essays), and their genre(s) (e.g., Science Fiction, Satire). Six of the authors on this list (24%) were women.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:164:The results of this simulation exercise are summarized in Appendix Table S12 (and the complete regressions used to estimate the effect of each simulated quota condition are presented in detail in Appendix Table S14). For women in Study 2 (see Appendix Table S12, Row 1), compared to the control condition, the descriptive feedback intervention increased the likelihood that participants selected biographies featuring female protagonists by 13.2 percentage points (B = 0.132, 95% CI = [0.031, 0.234], p = .011), and the simulated quota also significantly increased selections, by 18.5% (B = 0.185, 95% CI = [0.082, 0.289], p < .001), meaning feedback produced 71.4% of the benefit of a quota. For racial minorities in Study 3A (see Appendix Table S12, Row 2), compared to the control condition, the descriptive feedback intervention increased the likelihood that participants selected films featuring racial minority protagonists by 9.4 percentage points (B = 0.094, 95% CI = [0.042, 0.145], p < .001), and the simulated quota also significantly increased selections, by 17.1% (B = 0.171, 95% CI = [0.118, 0.225], p < .001), meaning feedback produced 54.7% of the benefit of a quota. For women in Study 3B (see Appendix Table S12, Row 3), compared to control condition, the descriptive feedback intervention significantly increased the likelihood of selecting films featuring female protagonists by 20.6 percentage points (B = 0.206, 95% CI = [0.150, 0.261], p < .001), while the simulated quota also significantly increased selections by 25.7% (B = 0.257, 95% CI = [0.201, 0.313], p < .001). This means offering descriptive feedback on the gender of past filmsΓÇÖ protagonists yielded 80.0% of the benefit of a gender quota. In Study 4A (see Appendix Table S12, Row 4), which examined racial diversity in author selections, compared to the control condition the descriptive feedback intervention significantly increased the likelihood of selecting authors from racial minority backgrounds by 13.4 percentage points (B = 0.134, 95% CI = [0.075, 0.193], p < .001), while the simulated quota also significantly increased selections by 29.6% (B = 0.296, 95% CI = [0.237, 0.355], p < .001), relative to the control condition, meaning that feedback achieved 45.3% of the effect of a quota. Finally, in Study 4B (see Appendix Table S12, Row 5), which examined gender diversity in author selections, compared to the control condition the descriptive feedback intervention significantly increased the likelihood of selecting female authors by 11.9 percentage points (B = 0.119, 95% CI = [0.060, 0.178], p < .001), while the simulated quota also significantly increased selections by 15.6% (B = 0.156, 95% CI = [0.096, 0.215], p < .001), meaning feedback produced 76.7% of the benefit of a quota.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:175:While our large sample sizes, diverse stimuli, and pre-registered experiments have many strengths, our research also has several important limitations. First, most of our studies rely on a fairly consistent paradigm. However, we systematically varied several design features across studies, including organizational context (e.g., whether participants were selecting NPR guests, books to be displayed at a library or on campus, or leaders to speak at a large conference), the base rates of underrepresentation in candidate pools, and outcomes measured (the selection of a single woman/racial minority vs. the proportion of women selected in a set). In most organizational settings, selection decisions and feedback will be more spread out over time and candidate pools will be less constrained than in our studies. For example, one candidate might be hired per quarter, and feedback might be provided at the end of the calendar year. Future research confirming that the effect weΓÇÖve documented here still arises when people face unconstrained candidate pools and extended decision and feedback timelines would be valuable. While it is possible that an extended decision timeline would decrease the size of feedback effects because feedback can become less salient over time (Tiefenbeck et al., 2018), the effect could also be magnified. Given the strength of the reputational and self-image concerns involved in the types of decisions we study, having more time to deliberate may provide a greater opportunity for evaluators to actively regulate their decisions and implement even more substantial corrections (Fazio, 1990; Plant & Devine, 2009). Additionally, while Study 5 demonstrates that feedback produces different effects depending on whether women are underrepresented or overrepresented, future research could explore the precise threshold at which feedback shifts from triggering motivation to respond without prejudice to triggering fairness concerns, though this threshold is likely context dependent.
