[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\r2_gdoc_text.txt:26:That said, we can hold the starting point constant by restricting to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute. We cannot directly measure what each participant considers an ΓÇ£appropriateΓÇ¥ level for a given attribute, but zero is a reasonable floor and is unlikely to reflect a deliberate level for most participants. In this analysis, we test the hypothesis that feedback motivates selection whenever the initial selections do not reflect appropriate levels. If that were the case, we should see feedback move participants for both race and gender and the comparison attributes in this subset. To test this hypothesis, we pooled participants across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B with participant-clustered standard errors, restricted to participant observations in which the initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute. We find that race and gender feedback increases the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority by +21.28 percentage points (p < .001, N = 1,222 across all five studies). Whereas, feedback about other attributes increases that probability by only +6.83 percentage points, and is not statistically significant (p = .21, N = 429). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients yields +14.46 percentage points (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.70, +26.21]).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\r2_gdoc_text.txt:42:Pooled (across studies) | Race/Gender Feedback | +21.28*** (N = 1,222) [+16.15, +26.42]
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\zero_restriction_response_codex.md:21:In a follow-up pooled analysis reported in the response letter, we restricted the data to participant observations in which the initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute. Among participants who initially selected zero women or racial minorities, race and gender feedback increased the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority on the final selection by 21.28 percentage points (p < .001, N = 1,222). Among participants who initially selected zero individuals with the comparison attribute, comparison-attribute feedback increased final selection by 6.83 percentage points, which was not statistically significant (p = .21, N = 429). A Wald test comparing the two pooled coefficients was significant (difference = 14.46 percentage points, p = .016). This analysis is imperfect because zero may sometimes reflect a deliberate preference and the comparison-attribute subset is meaningfully underpowered, but the pattern provides suggestive evidence against the possibility that comparison-attribute feedback fails to move selections only because those attributes were already being selected at appropriate levels.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:16:To address your concern that participants might already use comparison attributes ΓÇ£appropriatelyΓÇ¥ in their initial selections (potentially explaining why feedback about race and gender appears uniquely effective in our studies), we conducted a new pooled analysis restricted to participants whose initial selections contained zero of a given attribute, a conservative signal of underrepresentation that should provoke a reaction to feedback regardless of which attribute is involved. Within this sample, feedback about race or gender significantly increased the probability of subsequently selecting a woman or racial minority, whereas feedback about a comparison attribute (e.g., year of release, protagonistΓÇÖs profession) did not significantly change subsequent selections, and a Wald test confirms this difference is significant.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:44:We expect that a reputational or image concern is activated only after participants receive descriptive feedback suggesting that women and minorities have been vastly underrepresented in their past selections compared to the U.S. population. If underrepresentation of any group is responsible for our effects, then if the descriptive feedback we provided on some other selection attribute (say, the age of prior selectees) suggested a massive underrepresentation (say, of people over 50), this might drive a similar reaction. We conducted an additional analysis to try to address this possibility. Assuming that selecting 0 people with a given attribute would always signal underrepresentation, we test the hypothesis that feedback shifts in who is subsequently selected to make up for underrepresentation not just when it comes to race and gender but on any dimension. To examine this hypothesis, we pooled data from Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B (clustering standard errors by participant). We exclude Study 4A from this analysis because no participants in that study made initial selections containing zero of any of the comparison attributes, meaning there is no comparable ΓÇ£zero-baselineΓÇ¥ cell to contrast against the race/gender effect. We look only at observations involving participants who made an initial set of selections that included zero people, books, or movies with a given attribute (e.g., a set of films in Study X that included 0 YΓÇÖs or a set of books in Study Z that included 0 YΓÇÖs). We find that among participants who selected zero women or racial minorities initially, across all studies, race and gender feedback significantly increases the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority as their final selection, respectively, by 21.28 percentage points (p < .001, N = 1,222). Among participants who initially selected zero movies, books or XX with any of the other attributes under study (e.g., X, Y or Z), feedback informing them that 0% of their selectees had those other attributes did not significantly increase their probability of subsequently selecting an additional movie book, or XX with the relevant attribute (estimated effect =+6.83 percentage point; p = .21, N = 429). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients confirms that the pooled effect of feedback on subsequent choices is significantly larger when feedback is about the race or gender of initial selections than when it is about other features of initial selections (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.70, +26.21]). We have added several sentences to the Discussion section of Study 4 (p. X) summarizing these analyses and pointing the interested reader to a new appendix section describing the results in more detail.
